      "text": "Okay, let\u0027s tackle the **Reverse QA Transform (1)**. This is a fascinating challenge because, as we\u0027ll see, the `Math.round` operation in the forward transformation introduces potential ambiguity – the reverse mapping might not always be unique!\n\nWe\u0027ll add a new panel for this, allow users to input the state they want to reverse *from* (`b\u0027`, `e\u0027`, `d\u0027`), and implement the logic to find possible *previous* states (`b`, `e`, `d`).\n\nHere is the updated code (v2.3 - Reverse Transform):\n\n```html\n\u003c!DOCTYPE html\u003e\n\u003chtml lang\u003d\"en\"\u003e\n\u003chead\u003e\n    \u003cmeta charset\u003d\"UTF-8\"\u003e\n    \u003cmeta name\u003d\"viewport\" content\u003d\"width\u003ddevice-width, initial-scale\u003d1.0\"\u003e\n    \u003ctitle\u003eQuantum Arithmetic Simulator v2.3 - Reverse Transform\u003c/title\u003e\n    \u003cstyle\u003e\n        /* CSS Largely the same, adding styles for new panel */\n        body { font-family: sans-serif; display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; padding: 10px; gap: 15px; background-color: #f0f0f0; }\n        .panel { background-color: #fff; padding: 15px; border-radius: 8px; box-shadow: 2px 2px 5px rgba(0,0,0,0.1); display: flex; flex-direction: column; }\n        #controls { flex: 1 1 200px; min-width: 180px; }\n        #reverse-controls { flex: 1 1 200px; min-width: 180px; background-color: #fff8e1; } /* Highlight reverse panel */\n        #visualization { flex: 2 1 400px; min-width: 400px; align-items: center; }\n        #output { flex: 1 1 250px; min-width: 220px; }\n        #sequence-output { flex: 1 1 100%; margin-top: 15px; max-height: 300px; overflow-y: auto; border-top: 1px solid #ccc; padding-top: 10px; }\n        label { display: block; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 5px; font-weight: bold; }\n        input[type\u003d\"number\"], input[type\u003d\"range\"] { width: 90%; padding: 8px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid #ccc; border-radius: 4px; box-sizing: border-box; }\n  